1375–1420","1385–1424":"1385–1424","1400–1474":"1400–1474","1378–1425":"1378–1425","1405–1496":"1405–1496","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1343–1400":"1343–1400","1348–1412":"1348–1412"," 1400, age 56–57":"1400","1385":"1385","1425":"1425","after 1424":"na 1424","1348":"1348","1424":"1424","1412":"1412","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1474":"1474","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Sheriffhall House, Newton Parish, Edinburghshire, Scotland":"Newton Village, Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brightwell Baldwin, , Oxfordshire, England":"Brightwell Baldwin, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brewood, South Staffordshire Borough, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1385–after 1424":"1385–after 1424","1375–1420":"1375–1420","1385–1424":"1385–1424","1400–1474":"1400–1474","1378–1425":"1378–1425","1405–1496":"1405–1496","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1343–1400":"1343–1400","1348–1412":"1348–1412"," 1400, age 56–57":"1400","1385":"1385","1425":"1425","after 1424":"after 1424","1348":"1348","1424":"1424","1412":"1412","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1474":"1474","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Sheriffhall House, Newton Parish, Edinburghshire, Scotland":"Newton Village, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Brightwell Baldwin, , Oxfordshire, England":"Brightwell Baldwin, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Brewood, South Staffordshire Borough, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Giffard was born in 1385, in Oxfordshire, England, her father, Sir John Giffard, was 42 and her mother, Baroness Mary Whitmore, was 37. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with William Curzon. She died after 1424."},"et":{"1385–after 1424":"1385–pärast 1424","1375–1420":"1375–1420","1385–1424":"1385–1424","1400–1474":"1400–1474","1378–1425":"1378–1425","1405–1496":"1405–1496","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1343–1400":"1343–1400","1348–1412":"1348–1412"," 1400, age 56–57":"1400","1385":"1385","1425":"1425","after 1424":"pärast 1424","1348":"1348","1424":"1424","1412":"1412","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1474":"1474","1375":"1375","1405":"1405","Kedleston, Derbyshire, Engl